Bioeroding sponges are the principal endolithic bioeroders of tropical coral reefs and play an important role in marine ecological processes (e.g.
Bak 1976
;
Scoffin et al. 1980
;
Highsmith et al. 1983
). They can substantially harm growth­limited corals and cause significant loss in mollusc aquaculture (e.g.
Goreau & Hartman 1963
;
Alargaswami & Chellam 1976
). Because of these impacts, various scientific disciplines recently increased their efforts studying the biology of these sponges. It has been suggested that bioeroding sponges can be used as bioindicators of nutrient gradients (
Muricy 1991
) and to assess coral reef health (Holmes et al. 2000 ;
Sheppard et al. 2002
). Sponge abundances have been correlated with environmental changes caused by humans, and most markedly with eutrophication (
Rose & Risk 1985
; Holmes et al. 2000 ;
Rützler 2002 a
).

